Based on the search results, here's information about using **UXP fetch for HTTP external API server communication**:

## UXP Network APIs Overview

You may be looking for ways to make network calls for various reasons such as fetching an image, accessing a web API, browsing remote resources, synchronizing content, etc. UXP supports a range of network APIs that can fit your use case.(no content)UXP has fetch, XHR (XML HTTP Request), and WebSocket available in the global scope.

## Manifest Permissions Required

In plugins, you should seek permission for network access in the manifest and specify the domains of the endpoints. Please read about the manifest permissions module before you proceed.(no content)In order to leverage `fetch`, update the `manifest.json` with the `network.domains` permission. From UXP v7.4.0 onwards `permissions.network.domains` does not support wildcards in top-level domains.

## Basic Fetch Example

This sample app will show you how to load an image in an XD object (Rectangle or Artboard) by making network requests using XHR and fetch.

The Adobe XD example demonstrates a basic fetch pattern:
```javascript
const url = "https://dog.ceo/api/breeds/image/random";
return fetch(url)
  .then(function (response) {
    return response.json();
  })
  .then(function (jsonResponse) {
    // handle response
  });
```

## Code Samples Available

UXP provides fetch method globally, matching HTML DOM fetch method. See fetch for more details. See web-service-call-js-sample for an example plugin that communicates with a web server.(no content)You can use OAuth to connect to any supporting service that supports it, and provide online functionality in your plugin. See oauth-workflow-sample to see it in action.(no content)You can use websockets in UXP to communicate with other applications and processes.

## Known Limitations

There are two things that caught me by surprise in the fetch api that aren't mentioned in the documentation: Only https is supported (this is unfortunate for any localhost usage). The request is cached and it's unclear for how long and how to prevent this.(no content)There are a lot of use cases where running an HTTP/HTTPS server is essential to complete a workflow, including locally hosting a UI, completing OAuth workflows, and various interactions with other applications requiring HTTP/HTTPS communications. At the moment C++ Hybrid Plugins is the only way to accomplish this in UXP.

## Resources

- **Adobe Photoshop UXP Documentation**: https://developer.adobe.com/photoshop/uxp/2022/guides/code_samples/
- **InDesign UXP Network Recipes**: https://developer.adobe.com/indesign/uxp/resources/recipes/network/
- **Adobe XD Network Tutorial**: https://developer.adobe.com/xd/uxp/develop/tutorials/how-to-make-network-requests/


REMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks.

